          Seed black holes formed in the collapse of population III stars
          have been invoked to explain the presence of supermassive black
          holes at high redshift. It has been suggested that a seed black
          hole   can  grow  up  to  $10^{5\sim  6}\sunm$  through  highly
          super-Eddington  accretion  for a period of $\sim 10^{6\sim 7}$
